Full Description: Twonq is an online scheduling service that allows small businesses to create, maintain and share their schedules free of cost and in real time, 24 hours a day, every day! ABOUT TWONQ Twonq is the only free and easy service for individuals and businesses who want to create, maintain and share their schedules online and in real-time. Additionally, twonq is multi-lingual and location aware. Twonq updates your schedule automatically in Outlook and Google Calendar.  The service uses tags and Google Maps instead of directories like other such services. No more digging through pages of businesses. Tags make it easy to find the business you are looking for and businesses have more freedom to register their services. It's the new way to go. Each business is reviewed by twonqers and given a star rating. Visitors can quickly find a service provider based on their performance. Business owners are "twonqable" within minutes. The basic, fully functional, service is free of charge for businesses and their customers. Businesses can also subscribe for future additional services. twonq offers a widget to businesses, which they can include on their own webpage. This widget is used to make bookings and maintain a schedule. SOFTWARE AS A SERVICE (SAAS) twonq will offer an interface (API) which partners such as (online) directories, industry suppliers of SMB's can use to adopt the scheduling functionality of twonq into their own application and proposition. twonq.com is the website where businesses can register with twonq and customers can schedule appointments. It offers extensive configuration so that business can tailor their online agenda to fit the scheduling requirements of that specific business. twonq, the easiest way to book your day!

Description: Restaurant recommendation engine
Headquarters Regions: West Coast, Western US
Full Description: Qmato provides trusted restaurant recommendations. Users begin by filling out a brief, one-time questionnaire about their food, atmosphere, and value preferences. From there, it's one click to two great recommendations, tailored specifically to the user's tastes, anywhere in the US. Users can always get great recommendations without any fiddling, but if they're going on a date, planning a fancy dinner, wanting to try something unique, or just a particular cuisine, Qmato makes it easy to do that too. After getting the recommendations, if the user doesn't feel like eating a particular cuisine, or doesn't feel like paying that much or traveling so far, Qmato makes it easy to request a new recommendation that's a better fit. Qmato starts by recommending the very best personalized match based on the user's preferences, restaurant rating, and suitability for the occasion. If the user is staying in a place for more than one day, then variety becomes important too. So from one day to the next, Qmato gradually expands the pool from which it draws recommendations. That means users can get recommendations from Qmato every day and always end up at a new, interesting place.  Qmato's recommendations come with a brief explanation that explains why each restaurant is a great fit. Users can click through to see a full description of each restaurant. Qmato provides superb restaurant recommendations right from the start, but then goes further. As users rate restaurants, Qmato learns about their likes and dislikes and uses this information to make each user's recommendations even better over time. Qmato lists over 800,000 restaurants nationwide, so users can be confident its recommendations are truly the best options available. Qmato provides the full menus for hundreds of thousands of restaurants, often using direct links to the menu on the restaurant's own website - so users get the most up-to-date menu info available anywhere. Qmato also displays the business hours and other key details for hundreds of thousands of more places, so users always know what to expect. Qmato's Recommended list gives users a snapshot of the most unique and recommended items at nearly every restaurant. Users can also search for menu items to find the best burrito (etc.) in town. Often users will run across an interesting restaurant that just doesn’t fit the bill right now. Users can easily save these restaurants for later. They can keep track of their favorite places and make and share their own lists. Qmato also lets users browse full search results in two different views, write restaurant reviews, and follow other Qmato users to stay updated on their ratings, reviews, and lists. Qmato includes a powerful keyword search that can be used to find something specific or just unusual. Users can describe what they’re looking for in natural language - for example, “bright airy lunch spot” or “cheap vegetarian dinner” - and Qmato will return the most fitting results.
Industry Groups: Food and Beverage, Mobile, Sales and Marketing

Description: Tellus Aerospace is a Aerospace Product and Parts Manufacturing Industry
Headquarters Regions: San Francisco Bay Area, Silicon Valley, West Coast
Full Description: Tellus designs and manufactures acoustic liners to reduce noise generated by jet engines for business and commercial class aircraft. The product is based on NASA technology, which was licensed to the company after Tellus won the Space Race competition. Aircraft engines are extremely loud, and the situation is further impacted by ever increasing air traffic across the globe. To address the issue, the FAA and similar entities overseas have established a roadmap for stricter noise regulations at airports. By 2025 manufacturers must reduce noise by 39Db. Engine manufacturers themselves and existing acoustic treatment companies are developing various solutions for this problem. Tellus is focusing on the acoustic liner, which is a component of a jet engine that is designed to limit sound emissions. It is made from a strong, lightweight Ceramic Composite material with great temperature resistance. The key to our technology are that it is capable of multi-frequency sound suppression combined with a low-profile footprint.Even though current players are well established, our advantage in penetrating the marketplace is that our solution is complementary to current and developing technologies. The jet engine market is expected to top $500B in the next decade and noise reduction is a crucial factor for success of engine designs. The industry of aircraft engines is dominated by five major companies: GE Aviation, CFM International, Rolls Royce, Pratt & Whitney and International Aero Engines.  The business model consists of designing and manufacturing the product and selling directly to our target markets of business and commercial engine manufacturers. Our go-to-market strategy is to start working with business class engine manufacturers. Once we have proved the advantages of our solution in the business class engine market, we can then leverage that success to enter the commercial class market.  Company leadership consists of Russell Kirkman as CEO, with a background in materials research for high temperature composites in space applications from NASA Ames; Bruno Selva is the COO, who comes from Carnegie Mellon University, and is an accomplished entrepreneur with a successful history of establishing technology startups; and Yosune Casana as CTO, MSc. in Material Engineering, who has extensive knowledge of Ceramic Composites manufacturing and design for multiple industry applications.
Founders: Bruno Selva, Russell Kirkman, Yosune Casana

Description: Online Fundraising
Headquarters Regions: Midwestern US
Full Description: Our mission is to connect people with a cause. Everywhere we look, there is a decline in giving, especially amongst millennials. So we asked the question, why? We believe it's because organizations aren't catering to the needs of the younger generation. Millennials, like it or not, want to see transparency in where their money goes. How it's being used. What sort of impact is directly generated from the money they're giving. Traditional fundraising often lacks that level of intimate donating. Enter the new way to raise money online. The process is simple. Togetherr is built on a system of squares, numbered 1...2...3—all the way to, let's say 150 (or any other arbitrary number). When a user wants to donate, they simply select a square with the appropriate amount they'd like to donate. So if a user selects the square of 50, they'll donate $50. The next user can now donate the $49 square or $51 square, or any other available amount on the grid. Once all the squares are donated, the organization will have gross raised $11,325. A pretty sizable amount of money for a relatively small ask. The organization has asked 150 people for money, with the highest amount being $150, and they've raised over $11k. We think that's pretty neat!
